ref: Jour: Radiochimica Acta, Vol.91, Issue.12, p.689 (2003)
title: Measurement and calculation of radioactivities of spallation products by high-energy heavy ions

x4freetext: Measurement and calculation of radioactivities of
spallation products by high-energy heavy ions
Cyclotron and Radioisotope Center

x4codes.hlp: RIKEN (Inst. of Physical and Chemical Research), Wako, Japan
Nat.Inst. for Quantum & Radiol.Sci.& Tech., Chiba, Japan

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Radiochimica Acta, Vol.91, Issue.12, p.689 (2003)

x4freetext: - Target is natural.
- Chemical-form of target is element. Chemical
purities are 99.9% / 99.4% / 99.8% for copper,
aluminium and carbon target, respectively.
- Physical-form of target is solid.
- Target-thickness: HxWxT (mm) = 90x100x0.1 /
90x100x0.1 / 50x50x0.2 for cupper, aluminium and
carbon target, respectively.
Samples put on the front of surface were used
for measurements of the reaction cross section
and the mass-yield distributions or produced
nuclides, while samples inserted between the Cu
plates were used for measurements of the
spatial distribution of the residual activities
of produced nuclides in copper and of the
energy dependence of the cross section.

x4codes.hlp: Nat.Inst. for Quantum & Radiol.Sci.& Tech., Chiba, Japan

x4freetext: HIMAC facility
To measure gamma-ray spectra from samples
To monitor beam current during irradiation
- Error of peak efficiency: 0.5 to 7.2%
- Error of beam intensity: 1 to 6%
- Error of total counts of gamma-ray peak area: 1 to
Total error is 2 to 40%.
Spatial distribution of residual radioactivities in Cu
target assembly
Decay data of 11C are not shown in reference, but
obtained by private communication
Compiled file is reviewed by H.Yashima
